<div id="review_1650179719" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/1650179719" />
    <a title="Ritu" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8734607-ritu"><img alt="Ritu" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1620741233p2/8734607.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/1650179719?book_show_action=true">May 27, 2016</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ritu" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ritu" href="/user/show/8734607-ritu">Ritu</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Paperback 9780806503646" href="/book/show/376502.Spirits_Rebellious">review of another edition</a>


          <div>
    <span class="greyText">Recommended to Ritu by: </span>
      <a href="/user/show/11469485-soplada">Soplada</a>
  </div>


          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8734607-ritu?shelf=favorites">favorites</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer1650179719" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer7543052647969923226">Spirits Rebellious basically consists of three short stories combined with <b>Gibran&apos;s paintings</b> and his <b>lyrical style of writing </b>that makes you want to read more and let this guy make you believe stuff that you wouldn&apos;t have crossed your wildest dreams. It that ponders on the topics such as –<br/><br/>* How society judges you without knowing the facts.<br/><br/>* What we truly want vs what the society expects from us.<br/><br/>* What is actually right and what we are made to believe is right.<br/><br/><u>
  <b>Madame Rose Hanie</b>
</u><br/><br/>Madam Rose Han</span>
  <span id="freeText7543052647969923226" style="display:none">Spirits Rebellious basically consists of three short stories combined with <b>Gibran's paintings</b> and his <b>lyrical style of writing </b>that makes you want to read more and let this guy make you believe stuff that you wouldn't have crossed your wildest dreams. It that ponders on the topics such as –<br /><br />* How society judges you without knowing the facts.<br /><br />* What we truly want vs what the society expects from us.<br /><br />* What is actually right and what we are made to believe is right.<br /><br /><u>
  <b>Madame Rose Hanie</b>
</u><br /><br />Madam Rose Hanie is the story of a Rich <b>Married woman </b>who is gives up everything to be with her lover.<br /><br />She believes that she is closer to god and being faithful by not offering her body to somebody related to her by customs and traditions in exchange of bread when her heart belongs to another .<br /><br />So is she really an <b>Adulteress?</b><br /><br />Is it permissible for a woman to buy her happiness out of her husband's misery? <br /><br />Is it lawful for a man to enslave his wife's affection when he realizes he will never possess it ? <br /><br /><u>
  <b>The Cry of the Graves</b>
</u><br /><br />This story is all about <b>perspectives </b>that people have towards what is right and wrong.<br /><br />It is basically the <b>untold truth</b> which is never revealed because we don't give it an opportunity to be revealed because we chose to <b>Presume</b> .<br /><br />There are three incidents in this story which highlight how <b>Gullible and Judgmental </b>people are while following an <b>Autocratic leader</b>.<br /><br />Gibran says -<br /><br /><blockquote>
  <i> "When a man kills another man, people say he is a murderer, but when Emir (the King) kills him , the Emir is Just. When a man robs a monastery they say he is a thief,but when the Emir robs him of his life,the Emir is honourable. When a woman betrays her husband,they say she is a adulteress, but when the Emir makes her walk naked in the street and stones her later,the Emir is noble. Shedding blood is forbidden but who made it lawful for the Emir ?"</i>
</blockquote><br /><br /><br /><u>
  <b>Khalil the Heretic </b>
</u><br /><br />This is the story of an <b> Uprising</b> where the writer tries to evoke the rational side of people and make them shed their blind faith and break the ice about the wrong societal norms<br /><br />The writer tries to associate himself the the Protagonist here who has been expelled from the priest training because he tried to question the practices which he believed were complete opposite of what is right . <br /><br />I liked the part where he questions people by asking -<br /><br /><blockquote><i> Are you doing yourself justice when you lift your eyes towards lord almighty and then call him Father and then turn around ,bow your heads before a man and call him Master ? Are you contented ,as sons of god, with being slaves of man ? Did Christ not brethren you ? Yet sheikh Abbas calls you servants . Why are you hiding your souls in darkness ?.</i> </blockquote><br /><br />The best part of Gibran's writing is that you can't help but be moved by it and relate to it even though it was written <b>ages</b> ago. <br /><br />What I like about this book is that it has managed to be rebellious and rationale but at the same time not be violent. <br /><br />I bought all the books of the writer already and I am looking forward to read them all soon<br /></span>
  <a data-text-id="7543052647969923226" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


