<div id="review_3651406098" class="review nosyndicate" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3651406098" />
    <a title="Sabareesh" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8287122-sabareesh"><img alt="Sabareesh" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1577219492p2/8287122.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3651406098?book_show_action=true">Nov 18, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Sabareesh" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Sabareesh" href="/user/show/8287122-sabareesh">Sabareesh</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Hardcover " href="/book/show/36125679-spirits-rebellious">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3651406098" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer2977597852485227683">Kahlil Gibran is a gifted writer and in <i>Spirits Rebellious</i> he puts it all on display with pretty prose exploring age-old and yet everlasting themes such as the hypocritical nature of society which is manifested never better (or worse?) than when we give birth to and endorse customs and unwritten laws arising out of a certain spirit that are set exactly at odds against that very spirit. Gibran has an elegant way of viewing the world and he takes the reader along for the journey of pastoral Lebano</span>
  <span id="freeText2977597852485227683" style="display:none">Kahlil Gibran is a gifted writer and in <i>Spirits Rebellious</i> he puts it all on display with pretty prose exploring age-old and yet everlasting themes such as the hypocritical nature of society which is manifested never better (or worse?) than when we give birth to and endorse customs and unwritten laws arising out of a certain spirit that are set exactly at odds against that very spirit. Gibran has an elegant way of viewing the world and he takes the reader along for the journey of pastoral Lebanon while dissecting heavy topics such as power imbalances, class struggles, ever-present oppression and unfairness all with remarkable ease. <br /><br />The overuse of similes is the only blemish I can fault this book for, but Gibran makes up for it with his insightful parables hitting upon the general truths of the world that any reader will be hard-pressed to not feel connected to.</span>
  <a data-text-id="2977597852485227683" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

